  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug read-peripheral SPI1",
        "description": "Read SPI1 peripheral registers (SVD-decoded) to check SPE bit in CR1"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "**No \u2014 SPI1 is not enabled. `SPE` (CR1 bit 6) = 0.**\n\nThe entire CR1 register came back as `0x00000000`, so not a single bit is set. Here's what that tells you beyond just SPE:\n\n| CR1 Field | Value | Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| **SPE** (bit 6) | **0** | **Peripheral not enabled** \u2014 SPI1 is configured but never started |\n| MSTR (bit 2) | 0 | Master mode not selected either |\n| BR[2:0] (bits 5:3) | 0 | Baud = f_PCLK/2 (fastest; could be a default that was never tuned) |\n| CPOL / CPHA | 0 / 0 | Mode 0 (idle-low, first-edge sample) |\n| SSM / SSI | 0 / 0 | Hardware NSS management |\n\nThe most likely explanation is that the peripheral clock was enabled in RCC (enough for the register writes to stick), but the final `CR1 |= SPI_CR1_SPE` was never executed \u2014 a common omission when init code is split across HAL_SPI_Init() and MX-generated Enable calls. Worth also cross-checking that `RCC->APB2ENR.SPI1EN` is actually set; if that's 0 too, the bus clock itself is off and the register reads are returning reset-state from the bridge rather than real SPI1 state."
}